How bmi is interpreted with adults, according to the CDC healthy weight, nutrition, and physical activity

  • bmi < 18.5 is classififed as under_wt
  • bmi >= 18.5 and bmi <25 is classfified as normal_wt
  • bmi >= 25 and bmi < 30 is classififed as over_wt
  • bmi >= 30 is classififed as obesity. **This classififcation is used in the code below to segment customers based on weight
In [14]:
# created a new data frame with an additional feature in it called weight_rate. The new dataframe with an added feature is now called weight
weight = axis[['bmi','age','sex','children','charges','smoker','region']]
conditions = [(weight['bmi'] <18.5),((weight['bmi'] >= 18.5) & (weight['bmi']<25)),((weight['bmi'] >= 25) & (weight['bmi']<30)),(weight['bmi'] >= 30)]
values = ['under_wt','normal_wt','over_wt','obesity']
weight['weight_rate'] = np.select(conditions,values) 
weight

Statistical Data Analysis

2. Prove/disprove that the medical claims made by the people who smoke is greater than those who do not

We will test the null hypothesis

H0:1=2H0:1=2 ; Medical claim does not change with people's smoking status

against the alternate hypothesis

Ha:1>2Ha:1>2 ; Medical claim made by people who smoke is greater than those who do not smoke

Let's see if the T-test assumptions are satisfied or not

  • Medical claim cahrges are Continuous data
  • The sample has more than 30 samples and we can assume normal distribution
  • The two samples are from two independent populations ( smoker and non-smoker)
  • Unequal sample standard deviations, and we can assume the populations standard deviatins are different too.

  • Assume random sampling from the population

    We can use two sample T-test for this problem.

In [34]:
# customer segmentation as smoker and non-smoker
smoker = axis[axis['smoker']=='yes']
non_smoker = axis[axis['smoker']=='no']
In [35]:
#Importing required packages
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# Calculating p_value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(smoker['charges'], non_smoker['charges'], equal_var = False)
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  5.88946444671698e-103

Insight

  • The p-value is 5.88946444671698e-103, much less than the preset level of significance 0.05, as a result we can reject the null hypothesis, infavour of the alternative hypothesis. So, there is not enough evidence to conclude that smokers and non-smokers have equal medical claims. Medical claim made by people who smoke is greater than those who do not smoke.

3. Prove/disprove with statistical evidence that the BMI of females is different from males

We will test the null hypothesis

H0:1=2H0:1=2 ; There is no difference between the BMI of males and females

against the alternate hypothesis

Ha:12Ha:12 ; The BMI of males is different from females

In [36]:
# segmenting customers with sex and bmi
females_bmi = axis[axis['sex']=='female']['bmi']
males_bmi = axis[axis['sex']=='male']['bmi']
#axis[axis['sex']=='female'].std() = 11128.70
#axis[axis['sex']=='male'].std() = 12971.03
In [37]:
#Importing required packages
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# Calculating p_value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(females_bmi,males_bmi , equal_var = False)
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  0.08992430667834876

Insight:

  • The p-value is 0.0899 , which is greater than the set significance level of 0.05. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is an evidence to say that the BMI of males and females are not different significantly.

4. Is the proportion of smokers significantly different across different regions?

We will test the null hypothesis

H0:H0: The proportion of smokers is the same in all 4 regions

against the alternate hypothesis

Ha:Ha: The proportion of smokers is different in all 4 regions

5. Is the mean BMI of women with no children , one child, and two children the same?

Let's write the null and alternative hypothesis

Let 1,2,31,2,3 be means of BMI of women . We will test the BMI of women with no children, one child and 2 children

null hypothesis

H0:1=2=3H0:1=2=3: BMIs of women with one, two or 3 children are the same

against the alternative hypothesis

Ha:Ha: At least one BMI of women is different from the rest.

#import the required function
from scipy.stats import f_oneway
In [45]:
# perform one-way anova test
test_stat, p_value = f_oneway(axis.loc[(axis['children'] == 0) &( axis['sex']=='female'), 'bmi'],
                              axis.loc[(axis['children'] == 1 )&( axis['sex']=='female'), 'bmi'],
                              axis.loc[(axis['children'] == 2 )&( axis['sex']=='female'), 'bmi'])
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))

The p-value is 0.7158579926754841

Insight:

  • The p_value, 0.7 is greater than the set significance level of 0.05, therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is enough evidence to say that BMIs of women with no children, 1 child and 2 children are the same.
